In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command generates the table of contents at the point where it's placed. Each section, subsection, etc. (denoted by commands like `\section{}`, `\subsection{}`, and `\subsubsection{}`) will automatically be added to the ToC.

Please note that LaTeX needs to be run twice to properly generate the table of contents. This is because LaTeX generates an auxiliary file during the first run that it uses during the second run to populate the table of contents.

Also, the depth of sections that appear in the table of contents can be controlled using the `tocdepth` counter. For example, setting `\setcounter{tocdepth}{2}` will include sections and subsections, but not subsubsections, in the table of contents.

